post_text:
Round Rock ISD has improved student and staff safety by installing video intercom systems at all 55 campuses. Entrance doors on campuses are locked during school hours. To gain access to the front office, visitors will need to show identification and request entry through the video intercom system.

While on campus, all visitors are required to check-in at the front office. Intercoms are installed outside of the school’s front office. Visitors should be prepared to show their ID and state the nature of their visit to the front office staff using the video intercom system.

Campus visitors should allow for extra time and can avoid delays by calling ahead or making an appointment.

The video intercoms are part of the safety and security projects included in the voter-approved 2018 Bond.

Round Rock ISD will begin welcoming students back for on-campus learning, initially for students who are served primarily in self-contained special education settings — about 1 percent of students — on September 10. On September 15, District administrators plan to allow students who have selected on-campus learning as their preference to return to their schools. Only 30 percent of students are expected to return, a percentage that allows the District to allow for social distancing, enhanced adherence to health protocols, and minimize person-to-person contact.

Use link to continue reading this update (En Español).
http://ow.ly/hfJq50BbR00

Please share your thoughts on the District’s response to COVID-19 using Thoughtexchange https://my.thoughtexchange.com/#880318712. We value the input of our students, staff, parents and community members and use your feedback to inform decisions.

Round Rock ISD will begin UIL training activities for cross country, volleyball, football, and team tennis on Thursday, Aug. 20. Strength and conditioning and sport-specific drills will be allowed in accordance with the latest information from local health authorities and the UIL. All participation is voluntary. Coaches will contact families with more details.

Summer strength training camps, which were voluntary, were halted on June 26 due to public health conditions.

Coaches will follow UIL’s COVID-19 Risk Mitigation Guidelines, and Round Rock ISD will continue to monitor public health conditions closely and make decisions based on the latest data and guidance from local health authorities, the Texas Education Agency and the UIL.

Click through this post for a link to review UIL's COVID-19 Mitigation Guidelines: https://news.roundrockisd.org/2020/08/18/strength-and-conditioning-for-fall-athletics-to-resume-this-week/

Round Rock ISD Board of Trustees President Amy Weir has been selected as a member of the Texas Association of School Board’s 2021 Leadership TASB Class.

Weir will join an outstanding group of 28 school board leaders representing most of the 20 education regions in Texas to participate in a unique board development program. Leadership TASB exposes school board members to various issues, people, activities, and locations during a year-long program. Class members are selected for demonstrating leadership in their local district and communities and their representation of Texas school districts’ diversity.

Leadership TASB was developed and designed for school board members by school board members as part of TASB’s ongoing commitment to providing visionary leadership to Texas school boards. Members will learn from nationally known experts in education and business as they address themes and issues such as teamwork, trusteeship, equity, diversity, and visionary leadership.

https://news.roundrockisd.org/2020/08/10/board-of-trustees-president-amy-weir-selected-for-leadership-tasb/

Meal order forms assist Food Services in meal preparation, help avoid waste, and expedite checkout. Families only need to complete one request per family, with multiple children added to one form.

Parents/guardians who do not fill out the form for their student(s) may pick up meals when they present their student's ID or a document/report card with the student's ID printed.

Meal distribution will take place from Monday through Friday from 10 a.m. – 12 p.m. During meal distribution, lunch, and breakfast for the following day are provided. To pick up the meals, families should have the student name and ID written on paper and placed on the car's dashboard.

Lea esta actualización en español and more information, including curbside meal locations, meal prices, plus more, please visit https://foodservices.roundrockisd.org/

Tyler Hultman has been named the new principal of Fern Bluff Elementary School.

Hultman has served as the assistant principal of Pond Spring Elementary School since 2017 and, during that time, helped create a school-wide reward system that focused on positive student behaviors and reduced discipline referrals.

“While we all understand the challenges we face, I do not doubt that we will work together to make this a fantastic school year for everyone,” Hultman said. “As a collective group, we will continue to foster the strong traditions of Fern Bluff while paving the way for future achievements.”

This Research Connection program is for anyone in our community who's hoping to better understand how to support our youth in adapting to the recent stress and changes related to the COVID-19 pandemic, as well as how to promote mental health in our youth.

The American Foundation for Suicide Prevention Central Texas chapter presents host Dr. Jennifer Hughes—a licensed psychologist and Head of the Risk and Resilience Network in the UT Southwestern Center for Depression Research and Clinical Care (CDRC)—for this free online event.

Join Dr. Jennifer Hughes for a discussion of the current mental health challenges facing our youth and for tips to encourage resilience and wellness in youth.

All Round Rock ISD summer extracurricular and campus activities are canceled. The cancellations follow the order issued on July 14 by Travis County, which states all public and private schools in the county are to delay on-campus instruction until at least Sept. 7.

The order includes that no extracurricular sports or activities are allowed until school systems reopen for on-campus instruction. Round Rock ISD’s boundaries cover parts of both Travis and Williamson counties, as well as the cities of Round Rock, Austin, and Cedar Park.

Click through this post for more info with links thttps://news.roundrockisd.org/2020/07/15/round-rock-isd-cancels-summer-campus-and-extracurricular-activities/

Trustee Steve Math announced his plans to resign during the Board’s Regular Meeting on June 18 after serving as a Trustee since 2017.

Math, who serves in Place 6, is serving his second term on the Board, which expires in November 2022. During his service, he has been in leadership roles and served as the Board Vice President. During the action item regarding Math’s resignation, the Board discussed filling the vacancy, which they may do by holding a special election on Nov. 3, 2020. The special election for Place 6 would be in addition to the anticipated Trustee elections for Places 1,2, and 7, currently held by Nikki Gonzales, Charles “Chad” Chadwell, and Mason Moses, respectively.

In anticipation of the special election, information and applications for those interested in running for the Place 6 position can be found on the Round Rock ISD Board of Trustees website starting on July 15.

Click through this post to read the full story on the District website.
https://news.roundrockisd.org/2020/07/13/board-of-trustees-accept-steve-maths-resignation-discuss-next-steps/

post_text: Today we recognize Juneteenth, also known as Freedom Day - to celebrate the end of slavery on June 19, 1865. Texas was the last confederate state to have the 1863 Emancipation Proclamation announced, and in doing so, it freed and estimated 250,000 enslaved people.

MEAL SERVICE UPDATE: Round Rock ISD extends curbside meal distribution at 10 locations through Friday, July 31.

Curbside lunch and breakfast for the following day will continue to be served to students under the age of 18 Monday through Friday from 11 a.m. – 1 p.m. Weekend meals will also be available for students to pick up during meal distribution each Friday.

In alignment with the District’s academic calendar, meal distribution sites will not be open on Friday, July 3 as it is considered an official District holiday. In anticipation, families will be provided with meals for Friday and the weekend on Thursday, July 2.

Location information and more details: http://ow.ly/y9q450A9zqz

Coaches and staff are excited to welcome students back to campus and are working diligently to ensure safety protocols are in place and strictly followed.

Find more information and a link to the UIL website for guidelines, click through this post.

For questions or comments, please visit the District Facebook page at Facebook.com/rrisd.

post_text:
As an alternative to the traditional graduation ceremony, the Class of 2020 became the first to participate in Senior Commencement Walks.
With Pomp and Circumstance, Graduating seniors from the District's seven high schools crossed the stage. At the same time, their family stood on the field, celebrating the hard work their student put into achieving this milestone.

Although developed out of adversity, Senior Commencement Walks delivered pride, joy, and positive memories that families will remember beyond the obstacles they were designed to overcome.
Hear from our students and watch some of the memorable moments. Congratulations, Class of 2020! You did it!

Fern Bluff and Joe Lee Johnson elementary schools and McNeil, Round Rock, Stony Point and Westwood high schools were named Project Lead The Way (PLTW) Distinguished Schools for the 2019 – 2020 school year.

post_text:
Are you ready to shape the future of Texas? Join us at the Teaching Texans Virtual Career Event on June 10 from 1 - 4 p.m.

We are searching for teachers - both veteran and new - to provide students excellence in education.

You should attend if you are:
• seeking a full-time teaching role and are certified to teach in Texas.
• in a Texas Education Agency-approved certification program.
• certified in other states or countries and are having your credentials vetted by the Texas Education Agency.
• eligible for an interim or probationary certificate. Check out Texas Education Agency's certification resource page if you have questions about the process.

This is a come-and-go event—attend anytime between 1-4PM on June 10. Space is limited--registration is now open at teachingtexans.org!

post_text:
The final draft of Round Rock 2030, a comprehensive plan to shape Round Rock's future between 2020 and 2030, is scheduled to be presented to the City Planning & Zoning Commission for its recommendation on Wednesday, May 20, and then to the City Council for adoption on Thursday, June 25.

Both the May 20 and June 25 presentations will include public hearings with the opportunity for the public to comment on the Plan. Commenters may participate remotely, to preserve public safety.

If you're interested in viewing the plan draft, signing up to participate in the May 20 meeting and/or joining the Round Rock 2030 email list, use the link to go to the City of Round Rock website. http://ow.ly/uD0L50zHau7

In Spring 2019, the city held meetings within community quadrants to gather as much public input as possible to create a Comprehensive Plan that best serves the communities and businesses within the city.

In addition to live cams, the Cornell Lab’s All About Birds website offers bird guides, songs and sounds and other tips and information for fellow bird lovers.

FRIDAY’S FEATURED VIRTUAL FIELD TRIP

Today we are heading 1700 miles west to visit the Monterey Bay Aquarium in Monterey, California. There’s no need for scuba gear, just grab your device to see what’s 🎵under the sea. 🎵

Enjoy live cams of sharks, penguins, tropical fish, sea otters and other aquatic life. 🦈🐧🦑🐠🐡 While there, find the Aquarium’s free online classes and guided science activities for students in grades PreK-12.

Be sure to visit during Pacific coast daylight hours for the best live cam viewing experience.☀️

Aquarium Live Cams: https://www.montereybayaquarium.org/animals/live-cams
Resources for PreK-12: https://www.montereybayaquarium.org/for-educators/learning-at-home

Walking out of her home on a Tuesday morning, Forest North Elementary School Counselor Jill Peyton was surprised with the news that she had been named the District’s 2021 Elementary Teacher of the Year (TOY).

Surprising her with the news was Superintendent of Schools Steve Flores, Ph.D., Forest North Principal Amy Jacobs, and District staff.

post_text:
Round Rock ISD is engaged in a 5-year partnership with The Holdsworth Center to help us grow outstanding leaders at the district and campus levels. The leadership program is a two-year learning journey that develops leadership skills, practices growing, and empowering others to create change, driving excellent and equitable outcomes for students.

Teaching and Learning's Mandy Estes and Ryan Smith are alumni of The Holzworth Center's District Leadership Program. When faced with school closures due to the COVID-19 public health crisis, they leaned on their leadership skills to guide their principles for the work ahead. Read the full story on The Holdsworth Center website. https://holdsworthcenter.org/blog/round-rock-isd-guides-leaders-through-crisis/

🏆 Please join us in congratulating and honoring the excellence of our Round Rock ISD Teachers of the Year. Teachers are ROCK STARS and do great things every day. Campus peers and administration elect teachers of the year for their contribution in the classroom and throughout the campus learning community.

The District and State Teacher of the Year program awards designate teachers as such until the next school year. Therefore, they are awarded and named Teachers of the Year for the next year and not the current year.

Meet them: news.roundrockisd.org/category/toy-2021/

For the best interest of the health and safety of our students and staff, and accordance with direction provided by Texas Gov. Greg Abbott, Round Rock ISD schools and offices will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019 -2020 school year. Students will continue at-home learning until the semester ends on Thursday, May 21.

To access the latest information about the District’s response and decisions related to the COVID-19 public health crisis, please visit our COVID-19 School Closures webpage. roundrockisd.org/coronavirus/

Today we are keeping it local by virtually visiting the Zilker Botanical Gardens - the jewel in the ❤️ of Austin.

The Zilker Botanical Garden is nestled within Zilker Metropolitan Park. This park features the Taniguchi Japanese garden🎍, Hartman prehistoric garden🦕, a rose garden🌹, a cactus 🌵and butterfly garden 🦋 and more! 🌸🌺

So grab your device and let’s discover the beauty in our own backyard.

Website: https://zilkergarden.org/

UPDATES: Meal Service During School Closures

ℹ️ No meal service on Friday, April 10. Originally scheduled as a non-instructional school holiday, meal service will not be provided on Friday, April 10. During service on Thursday, April 9, Food Services will offer weekend meals and Monday's breakfast.

Weekday meal service is from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. at 13 locations. Students pick up lunch for the day and breakfast for the following morning.

NEW*** With verification, children are not required to be present for parents to pick up meal(s). The District is required to verify student eligibility for each meal. This means that parents/guardians can pick up meals for students without the child being present, and each meal must provide verification of the student’s eligibility.

Visit the Food Service website for meal distribution locations and eligibility information. http://ow.ly/q4BG50z8UdY

post_text:
Monday, April 6 marks the first day of at-home online learning. We are incredibly proud of our students, families, and staff for your patience, flexibility, and resilience as we endeavor, together, in this new opportunity.

The Parent Guide to At-Home Learning offers tips for how to prepare students for the at-home learning environment. The guide also includes a Google Classroom parent’s overview video. Presented in English and Spanish.

At-home learning is new, different, and temporary. We eagerly await to resume instructing, guiding, and encouraging students in-person on our campuses.

Printed take-home packets will continue to be available at our curbside breakfast and lunch distribution sites for students who would prefer printed materials or who may continue to have limited access to devices or the Internet.

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/16a4bxrTCYPlvt31_TASiI5Kbse_EO5OhU8dyLUsTv58/edit#slide=id.g7b9f1d1ff7_0_0

This next 48 hour Challenge is going to be awesome. Show us what your student can create with Legos®️.

Who’s got the skillzzz? 👷🏾‍♀️

Deemed critical need supplies, Round Rock ISD donated approximately 6,500 surgical masks and 7,000 pairs of gloves to the Williamson County Emergency Operations Center.

Elaine Douville, Round Rock ISD director of health services, with her team of school nurses, took inventory and assessed what supplies the District could provide to the county to help our front line first-responders during the COVID-19 pandemic. Click through this post to read the full story reported by Community Impact.

post_text:
The College Board has posted an update to address the needs of students who participate in AP classes.

As we continue to become aware of information that impacts students, we will share the information here.
shared_text:
The College Board
March 16 at 1:26 PM ·

The College Board is developing tools to mitigate the impact of school closures on students in the Advanced Placement Program. All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. We’re working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit they’ve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Board’s focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

Throughout Spring Break, we will be working with our public health agencies regarding decisions on school closures and other responses related to the COVID-19 pandemic. We will inform our community by Thursday, March 19, if the return date for students or staff is later than March 23.

Camps run weekly June 1 through July 30 with prices starting as low as $129 per week. Explore cool summer fun, and academic enrichment camps at summercamp.roundrockisd.org/

Middle school students have a wide variety of camp choices providing fun and imagination with activities in art, crafts & DIY, music and theatre, sports and fitness, engineering, coding, and academics, plus so much more.

Summer camps that help build academic and coding skills are available for high school students.

Camps are held at three convenient District locations:
- Herrington Elementary School, 2850 Paloma Lake Blvd., Round Rock, TX 78665
- Pearson Ranch Middle School, 8901 Pearson Ranch Rd., Austin, TX 78717
- Grisham Middle School, 10805 School House Ln., Austin, TX 78750

Bring a friend. Round Rock ISD Summer Camps are open to the community, which means you don’t have to be a student enrolled at a District school to attend summer camps.

Visit the Summer Camp website summercamp.roundrockisd.org/ for more information and to explore camps.

-Posted by the Round Rock ISD Facebook Administrator-

post_text: The Round Rock ISD Board of Trustees held a workshop on Feb. 13, 2020, to discuss potential adjustments to boundaries in areas of the District and receive public feedback. The evening focused on possible adjustments to the Elsa England, Caraway, Herrington, and small portions of the Teravista attendance areas to address campus capacity and prepare for the opening of Elementary 35 in Fall 2021. Also being considered for potential adjustment are the Joe Lee Johnson and C.D Fulkes feeder patterns to address middle and high school alignment.

Board Briefs: Boundary Review 2020 Workshop
text:
The Round Rock ISD Board of Trustees held a workshop on Feb. 13, 2020, to discuss potential adjustments to boundaries in areas of the District and receive public feedback. The evening focused on possible adjustments to the Elsa England, Caraway, Herrington, and small portions of the Teravista attendance areas to address campus capacity and prepare for the opening of Elementary 35 in Fall 2021. Also being considered for potential adjustment are the Joe Lee Johnson and C.D Fulkes feeder patterns to address middle and high school alignment.

Brushy Creek Elementary School students are having far-out fun in their very own Spacelab. Spacelab is an immersive transformable experience for lessons centered around space exploration, STEM, and a variety of other critical thinking activities.

The transformation was made possible through Partners in Education Foundation and PTA grants. It took 10 volunteers more than 1,500 hours to create this out of this world learning environment.

The Austin Statesman has named students from Round Rock and Westwood high schools as "ones to watch" as they head to compete in Texas UIL Swimming and Diving Championships this weekend. statesman.com/sports/20200213/uil-state-swimming-and-diving-championships-12-central-texans-to-watch

🏊‍♂️Adam Haig, senior, Round Rock: Competes in the 100 backstroke and 200 individual medley.

🏊‍♂️Vincent Ribeiro, senior, Round Rock: Is defending Class 6A champ in 200 individual medley and will compete in the 100 breaststroke.

🏊‍♀️KyAnh Truong, junior, Westwood: Finished fourth in state last year, she qualifies again with the second-fastest time in 50 freestyle. She is also in 100 freestyle.

Read KyAnh's student athlete profile in the Statesman's Faces of the Field.

Best of luck to ALL the dedicated athletes competing this weekend.

Students from across Round Rock ISD showed off their artistic talents during opening of the RRock Print exhibit earlier this week! The printmaking focused exhibition is in conjunction with the professional citywide festival PrintAustin and will be on display at the Cedar Ridge Auditorium until Feb. 22.

Visit the gallery to see photos from the event!

Two Round Rock ISD freshmen are Austin area Leukemia & Lymphoma Society (LLS) Student of the Year candidates. They are hosting a seven-week campaign to raise money for LLS.

post_text:
Superintendent Steve Flores, Ph.D., announced today the selection of Amy Grosso, Ph.D., as Round Rock Independent School District’s first-ever Director of Behavioral Health.

The newly created position is aimed at improving student academic achievement and well-being by providing mental health services and will include overseeing programs for students who are in crisis or at-risk due to depression, grief, suicidal ideation, anger, inadequate social skills, disruptive behavior or family problems.

COMMUNITYIMPACT.COM
Round Rock ISD awarded in school architecture competition

Friends of Texas Public Schools
January 21 at 8:20 AM ·

It's cool to choose a Texas public school!

Round Rock ISD awarded in school architecture competition for its Nature to Neighborhood Studio at Laurel Mountain Elementary School.

The Caudill Award winners were chosen from among 34 projects awarded in the areas of community, planning, transformation, design, value and sustainability.

The competition is hosted by the Texas Association of School Administrators and Texas Association of School Boards for projects that exemplify excellence in planning and design of the learning environment, the release said.

Boundary Hearings begin this week! During the meetings, District staff will present proposed changes, demographic information, and the anticipated impact on enrollment and community members will have the opportunity to provide feedback.

Meetings this week:

Elsa England Elementary: Tuesday, January 21, 6 p.m.
Herrington Elementary: Wednesday, January 22, 6 p.m.
C.D. Fulkes Middle: Thursday, January 23, 6 p.m.

For information on potential adjustments and how to watch meetings live visit the Boundary 2020 website.
